ether, in Teamflow.=C2=A0
Teamflow brings collaboration and communication into one place. In The Arc =
of Collaboration [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uxCAMhU8z7CbCQP4W=
LLrpNSICngkKgQicjnL70mRRCT0LPdnP_qwhfKd86j0VYn8y0bmjjvgpAYkws6NgnrzT0IlBtmp=
kTisHQzswX6ZXRtyMD5rygWw_5uCtIZ_i1cG5aNmiRe84cs7VrMD27mWdM_2gOjWYuRt7c-eaw3=
mMFjX-YD5TRBb0QrSXh_x6iO_61k9a7WJ8bGza6l9wGGvhQxXoqtCCT5PtM72eNoVg5pSvZarFv=
BZcAAeQINtOjg00YXErxJIO-VB8e4umHHMhY9e_-SzrmKhO8PFd7XUxG4bLqFdOtW5H9HROGM0c=
0N0A6OZ4IZneGLHmo5sMVXrAW9XBOKqW3wdXQhIAuBglq8ku1a74H_oLHY6J4Q], Kevin Kwok=
 wrote about the =E2=80=9Cmeta-coordination layer=E2=80=9D for work:
There is a need for a layer across all the applications. A layer for things=
 that should be shared across the apps as well collaborative functionality =
across them.
There is some mix of presence, collaboration, coordination, and identity th=
at should be ubiquitous across whatever apps are being used. A layer more a=
ttached to the people doing work and what they=E2=80=99re trying to accompl=
ish=E2=80=94than which specific app they=E2=80=99re in.
That sounds an awful lot like what Flo and the team are building at Teamflo=
w.=C2=A0
In Slack: The Bulls Are Typing=E2=80=A6 [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/e=
JxVkMFuhSAQRb_msdMwIFYXLLrpbxiUUclDMDC08e9Ln0mbJsBkcpm5uWcxhFtMlz5jJvbzTHSd=
qAN-ZY9EmFjJmCZnNfRikKobmdWdhUENzOVpTYiHcV5TKsjOMnu3GHIxvCY4F4rt-k2sdu3VuK7=
I7TC8daLvOK7juqgFhITb1xTrMCyo8RPTFQMyr3eiMz_k-0N81BMizTG5sLW5zJnM8myXeFThrD=
f72je0YzMX73NjEjY1Sv3NnBZcAAeQIFUvxxZav9snhByLfHT82MS_jSzpX6sqP3dzoH8JNeBU6=
1GCo2vCYGaP9s5ON8IXjWnDgKmitZOhCg646noYx07xO2uFIwGAi1Gy6mxjnQp_pt_bZosl], I=
 wrote that such a product could be a Slack killer. I believe that even mor=
e after seeing Teamflow: since it adds a spatial layer to collaboration sof=
tware, which multiplies the number of potential apps that can be embedded i=
nto Teamflow versus Slack.=C2=A0
After I wrote about Slack, Salesforce acquired it for $27.7 billion, both v=
alidating the size of Teamflow=E2=80=99s opportunity and making it less lik=
ely that Slack develops the meta-coordination layer itself. Have you tried =
using Salesforce?=C2=A0
That leaves a huge opening for Teamflow, and I actually think that $27.7 bi=
llion undersells the opportunity. Slack was born in an office-first world. =
Teamflow is born in a remote-first era, and remote is poised to become the =
next big platform shift for enterprises. While Slack=E2=80=99s promise was =
killing email, if Teamflow is successful, it might take down an even more d=
espised foe: the scheduled meeting.=C2=A0
No unnecessary meetings. All your work tools in one place. No commute. Sere=
ndipity.=C2=A0=C2=A0
While the benefits of remote work are potentially immense, a post-COVID rem=
ote-first world isn=E2=80=99t guaranteed. It will take products like Teamfl=
ow, and people like us to join the movement.=C2=A0
We Might Be Going Back.. Unless We Do Something
Anyone who has been fortunate enough to get to work from home over the past=
 year has gotten a taste of the benefits (and some downsides, but just know=
 that your kids will eventually go back to school).=C2=A0 Today, the benefi=
ts of remote work are mainly non-work-related: no commute, more time with f=
amily, freedom to travel, etc=E2=80=A6 The work part is still sub-par, thou=
gh, because we=E2=80=99re using tools designed for an office-first world.=
=C2=A0
Teamflow is more than an enterprise SaaS product; it=E2=80=99s on a mission=
 to accelerate the transition by making remote work more enjoyable and prod=
uctive than the physical thing. Flo believes it=E2=80=99s the highest impac=
t return-for-effort he can possibly achieve, because remote work can:=C2=A0
Give everyone 54 minutes a day back in commute time.=C2=A0
Unlock opportunity for everyone.=C2=A0
Create the biggest labor market in the world with hundreds of millions of p=
eople.
Make it 10x easier to find a job or hire people.
Make people happier at work.
Teamflow is redesigning what work can be like when physical limitations are=
 removed. The opportunity if they get it right is massive: CEBR estimates [=
https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUUuOhSAQPM1jp-GjjC5YzGauYRBaJU_BQDM-bz=
-oi0kIFF1dFKk2GmEO8VR7SEiubcBzB-XhSCsgQiQ5QRycVUzyTrRNT6xqLOvajrg0TBFg025VG=
DOQPY-rMxpd8LeCUt6SRUlhJJv41HWy-WJd0xkpbdt22srejNQ8vjpbB96Agl-IZ_BAVrUg7ukl=
vl_8p6zjOGrjMLpPbcJWCiZ4BI8FWX3fb7IA8ENOVzmYvJWOCx-LQ6h2vUO8Ooo2bM5Ubtu1wVR=
NK3zcuEJ1hPh2fq5yqjhlfb3biTjFKWeUMcFEK0Vfs3pd7Jv5FLJ4NXSbeZ3ymFCb9_U3EpUPOI=
ZYHir0e9EbrDdRIhrKuWXv8BzA62Jpn_TwGcKd5zCDh1iGYweNJXpG20ayvm9a-qRV4hWMMcp7Q=
YqzDUXl_03_AJXhodA] a $2.3 trillion (with a T) potential impact to GDP from=
 remote =E2=80=94 just in the US.=C2=A0
I assumed, as I wrote in We=E2=80=99re Never Going Back [https://email.mg2.=
substack.com/c/eJxVkM1uwyAQhJ8m3GKx_NjmwKGXvgbCsLVRbLAAN_Lbl8RSq0osHGaH0XzO=
